<DocsLayout title="Zero-Config Onboarding" description="Paste your product URL and agents deploy automatically — AI extracts pain points, keywords, and subreddits in seconds.">
  <h1>Zero-Config Onboarding</h1>

  <p style="margin-top: 16px;">
    LeadEcho's onboarding wizard lets you go from zero to monitoring in under 60 seconds.
    Paste your product URL, review the AI-generated setup, and deploy. No manual keyword research,
    no guessing which subreddits to monitor.
  </p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>

  <pre><code>Step 1: Enter product URL
     |  https://yourproduct.com
     v
Step 2: AI scrapes & analyzes
     |  Extracts: product name, description, features,
     |  pain points, competitors, target audience
     |  Generates: keywords, subreddits, platform selection
     v
Step 3: Review & customize
     |  Edit any field — add/remove pain points,
     |  keywords, subreddits, platforms
     v
Step 4: Deploy agents
     |  Profile created, embeddings generated,
     |  keywords activated, monitoring starts
     v
Inbox populates within 5 minutes</code></pre>

  <h2>What the AI Extracts</h2>

  <p>
    When you submit a URL, LeadEcho scrapes the page content and passes it to the configured
    LLM provider (GLM or OpenAI) with a structured extraction prompt. The AI returns:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Field</th>
        <th>Description</th>
        <th>Example</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>product_name</code></td>
        <td>Product name extracted from the page</td>
        <td>Acme SaaS</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>description</code></td>
        <td>One-sentence product description</td>
        <td>Infrastructure monitoring for DevOps teams</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>features</code></td>
        <td>3-8 key product features</td>
        <td>Real-time alerts, custom dashboards, ...</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>target_audience</code></td>
        <td>Who the product is for</td>
        <td>SRE teams at mid-size companies</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>pain_points</code></td>
        <td>5-10 problems the product solves</td>
        <td>"Too many false alerts", "Expensive monitoring tools", ...</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>competitors</code></td>
        <td>Competitor names mentioned or implied</td>
        <td>Datadog, New Relic, Grafana Cloud</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>suggested_keywords</code></td>
        <td>5-15 monitoring keywords</td>
        <td>Product name, competitor names, pain-point phrases</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>suggested_subreddits</code></td>
        <td>3-8 relevant subreddit names</td>
        <td>devops, sysadmin, kubernetes, sre</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>suggested_platforms</code></td>
        <td>Best platforms for your product type</td>
        <td>reddit, hackernews, devto</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>URL Scraping</h2>

  <p>
    LeadEcho uses a two-tier approach to scrape product URLs:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Scrapling sidecar</strong> (primary) — If the Scrapling browser sidecar is running,
    it navigates to the URL with anti-bot bypass and returns clean page text.</li>
    <li><strong>HTTP fallback</strong> — If Scrapling is unavailable, a simple HTTP fetch extracts
    visible text from the page body, stripping <code>&lt;script&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;style&gt;</code>,
    <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code> tags.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Page text is truncated to ~8,000 characters before being sent to the LLM — well within
    context limits for GPT-4o-mini or GLM-4.5-flash.
  </p>

  <h2>What Gets Created</h2>

  <p>When you click "Deploy Agents", LeadEcho creates:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Monitoring profile</strong> — With your product name and description.</li>
    <li><strong>Pain-point embeddings</strong> — Each pain point is embedded via Voyage AI and stored
    as a 1024-dim vector for semantic matching.</li>
    <li><strong>Keywords</strong> — One keyword entry per suggested keyword, configured for the
    selected platforms and subreddits.</li>
    <li><strong>Onboarding state</strong> — Marked as complete in workspace settings.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The background monitor picks up the new keywords on its next 5-minute tick and begins
    crawling immediately.
  </p>

  <h2>Manual Setup Fallback</h2>

  <p>
    If you prefer to configure everything manually, click "Skip — set up manually" on the URL
    input step. This drops you into an empty review form where you can type your product name,
    pain points, keywords, and platform selection from scratch.
  </p>

